title: [Install] update the installation docs recomending the python -m rubrix.server way

labels.name: type: documentation
labels.description: Improvements or additions to documentation

body:
The idea is following default installation:
```bash
# install server dependencies
pip install rubrix[server]

# if no ES running
docker run ...

# run web app
python -m rubrix.server
```

advantage: 
- without docker-compose: easier to update the rubrix version
- with ES container running in the background, easier to avoid data loss
- we advocate only one way to start the web app, docker-compose is an extra that can still be used by "experts"

disadvantage:
- we include the server dependencies in the default installation, installation is not as lightweight as before

note:
- in the conda package we need to update the dependencies

title: [Search] Enable results highlighting for textual fields

labels.name: type: enhancement
labels.description: Indicates new feature requests

labels.name: area: server
labels.description: Indicates that an issue or pull request is related to the server

body:
Find a way to return highligthting info with search results. We can exploit the [elasticsearch highlighting](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/highlighting.html) keeping in mind that, for text classification, highlighting for multiple fields is not trivial when no default string searches.

For example, given a dataset with records including  `inputs.subject` and `inputs.body` the query:
```
size weight
```
could match terms in `inputs.subject`, `inputs.body` or both.

But, if we select a field in query:
```
inputs.subject: (size weight)
```

the highlight results could bring info for both fields `subject` and `body`, resulting in highlighting information that is not totally truthful

title: [Search] Improve and normalizes the search data model

labels.name: type: enhancement
labels.description: Indicates new feature requests

labels.name: area: server
labels.description: Indicates that an issue or pull request is related to the server

body:
Things to keep in mind:

- Normalize text inputs fields: `text`, `inputs`, `words` must be normalized and use a common pattern for all tasks
- Several es analyzers for text fields: `standard` and `whitespace`(?) for fine tuning searches. Default as `standard`
- What about text fields in metadata ? For now, only terms queries are supported. It's mean that metadata fields with large content are not enabled to be queries as full text search.
- Created indices should contain mapping info only for its fields. A text classification index should not include mapping info for tokens or text predicted (text2text).
- Review filter fields and align with UI names (if any)
- What about nested fields? like token or metrics info for token classification, or label and its score for text classification. As default, query string dsl does not support nested queries, but it could be nice include some minimal support for that kind of queries.

@dvsrepo @dcfidalgo Anything to include here?


## Tasks

To achieve to do the work, we need tackle following tasks (that will be created as separated issues and linked here)

1. [Datasets] Avoid using global template for all indices
2. [Datasets] Dataset migration mechanisms for each release
3. [Datasets] New es document model per task with backward compatibility fields
4. [Datasets] Apply migration to new es doc model 
5. [Datasets] Build searches and aggregations using new doc model

title: [weak supervision] Feedback on skweak tutorial
body:
Hi @ruanchaves, I finally found a free slot to go through the tutorial. Here's a detailed review:

1. I'd try to streamline the preprocessing part. Maybe create a preprocessed dataset and move the preprocessing part to an appendix? The in the preprocessing section we just describe the data format.
2. As a minor comment for the tag_set we could use `dataset["train"].features["ner_tags"].feature.names`.
3. We strip BI tags, I would add a short sentence saying why we need to do this.
4.I'd try to log the conll train split (without tags) in Rubrix right at the start, so you can test some of the heuristics (for example the company ones, I guess that as conll is an English corpus we could remove `sa` and `ag`, and maybe even find some other suffix that work more or less well?). Also in terms of the workflow and support by Rubrix I believe that including this step adds some value, as you are able to verify your hypotheses by directly searching.
5.  Question: In the gazetteers part, if the conclusion after exploring is that only the wiki gazetteer is working, we should explain what to do, do we don't make use of the other gazetteers? 

The most fundamental issue that I see is: *using conll for evaluation and only defining lfs and aggregating on companies and orgs*. I believe this comes from the fact that we are reusing much from the original skweak tutorial which actually builds a NER model with those entities only. This is likely one reason the final models are underperforming. More specifically:

1. Our `hmm_model = CustomHMM("hmm", ["COMPANY", "OTHER_ORG"])` ignores `PER` and other `MISC` entities from the pre-trained model lf. I have checked this after the first Rubrix logging, you can see there are no `PER`, etc. In any case, if we don't add lfs for at least PER and maybe other MISC, it won't make much sense because the only supervision source will come from the spaCy model.
2. If I understand correctly, we then train a spaCy model with mainly the `hmm` labels, falling back to the pre-trained spaCy annotations if we have no ents for a record. So the only source of PER and other MISC is this fraction of the records (those with no annotation from the hmm) and as said earlier only from this one source of supervision.
3. Another general thing: NER training sets and models largely benefit from unlabelled examples, this is examples where there shouldn't be any entity. I'd like to make sure we are training the end models with examples with no entities.
4. More of a question: couldn't we do the MISC alignment before defining the labelling functions, instead of before training?

I guess that's it. Recap:

1. Streamline the pre-processing part.
2. Make use of Rubrix search capabilities from the start to define the heuristics (we can later in the same PR provide a video)
3. If we decide to evaluate on conll we should include heuristics for PER and MISC, and include them in the HMM aggregation process. Other option is focus only on improving the performance for the ORG label, and thus: 1) evaluate ORG performance with the pre-trained spaCy model (by using only that entity label from conll), 2) build an skweak training set with lfs and the pre-trained model, and 3) evaluate ORG performance with models trained on this dataset (with the hope they improve over the pre-trained model baseline).

We can go through this tomorrow.
